CHAPTER 4: THE PLAN
My office looks legitimate.
That's the whole point.
"Brennan Property Solutions" - the sign's on the door in tasteful serif font. Small reception area. Jennifer at the front desk, typing away, answering phones like this is a real business. In a way, it is. We buy properties. We process transactions. We file the paperwork.
We just don't mention where the money comes from.
I'm at my desk, staring at three computer screens. Left screen: property listings. Middle screen: purchase agreements and wire transfer confirmations. Right screen: the spreadsheet that tracks everything Vincent Harlan owns in Los Angeles.
Forty-seven buildings. And counting.
I light a cigarette even though Jennifer hates it. She doesn't say anything. Smart girl.
My phone rings. Unknown number. But I know exactly who it is.
"Brennan."
"Mr. Brennan." The voice is smooth, professional. Vincent's lawyer. Never gives his name. Doesn't need to. "Confirming the Koreatown property closes today."
"Signed this morning. Funds transferred. Clean."
"Purchase price?"
"Three point two million."
The building's worth maybe one point eight. The extra one point four? That's dirty money I just made clean. Inflated appraisal. Fake comparable sales. Cash buyer that's actually a shell company owned by another shell company owned by Vincent.
It's art. Ugly, criminal art. But art.
"Excellent. Mr. Harlan appreciates your efficiency."
I take a drag. "Just doing my job."
"He has another property. Boyle Heights. Residential building. Needs processing by next week."
My stomach drops. "Boyle Heights?"
"Yes. The rents are... underperforming. Mr. Harlan wants it repositioned."
Translation: Evict the poor families, renovate cheap, double the rent, fill it with people who can't afford to complain.
"Send me the details."
"Of course. And Mr. Brennan? Six years of impeccable work. Mr. Harlan considers you... irreplaceable."
The word hangs in the air like a noose.
"I'm not going anywhere."
"Good. Because people who try to leave Mr. Harlan's employment tend to have unfortunate accidents. I'm sure you understand."
He hangs up.
I sit there, cigarette burning down to the filter. Stare at the screens. Forty-seven buildings. Thousands of families. All living in properties I made "legitimate." All paying rent that flows back to Vincent. All trapped in a system I built with spreadsheets and signatures.
Jennifer pokes her head in. "Cole? The inspection report for the Vernon property is here. They're saying it needs two hundred thousand in foundation work."
"Get me a contractor. We'll do four hundred thousand in renovations."
She frowns. "The building doesn't need four hundred—"
"The building needs whatever the invoice says it needs." I don't look at her. "Get it done."
She leaves. Doesn't question it. That's why I hired her. Smart enough to do the work, not smart enough to ask why.
I pull up the Boyle Heights address they just sent. Cross-reference it with my files. It's in a neighborhood I've processed three other buildings in. South LA. Heavy gang presence. Families barely scraping by.
I open a hidden file on my desktop. Spreadsheet. Different from the others. This one tracks money Vincent doesn't know about. Money I've been skimming for three weeks.
Forty-seven thousand dollars.
Taken in tiny amounts. Five hundred here from an inflated inspection. A thousand there from a fake contractor invoice. Two thousand from a purchase price bumped just slightly higher than Vincent asked for.
Not enough to trigger an audit. Just enough to fund what I need.
A safehouse. Equipment. Surveillance gear. Guns.
I'm using Vincent's money to destroy Vincent.
The irony would be funny if it wasn't potentially fatal.
I close the laptop. Tell Jennifer I'm doing site visits for the afternoon. Get in my car. Check my mirrors three times before I pull out. Paranoia's kept me alive for six years. Not stopping now.
Twenty minutes later, I'm across town at a storage unit in El Segundo. Unit 237. Paid in cash under a fake name. This is my real office.
No Jennifer. No tasteful fonts. Just maps, photos, files, and evidence pinned to every surface like a serial killer's lair.
Except I'm not hunting people.
I'm hunting a system.
Ray's already there when I arrive. Sitting in a folding chair, my old notebook open in his lap. He looks up. Looks almost sober. Almost.
"You look like shit," he says.
"I've been up for thirty-six hours. What's your excuse?"
"Existing."
I lock the door behind me. "You read through it?"
He taps the notebook. "Yeah. Your network map is... comprehensive."
"Six years of receipts. Every building, every shell company, every transaction I processed." I light another cigarette. "Vincent owns this city. I'm going to take it from him piece by piece."
Ray closes the notebook. Looks at the wall behind me - red string connecting photos, names, addresses. Like a conspiracy theorist's wet dream.
"So who do we hit first?"
"Marcus Delgado." I pull a photo down. Mid-forties, overweight, cheap suit. "Property manager. Handles about twenty buildings for Vincent's various LLCs. Does the evictions, collects the under-the-table payments, keeps tenants scared."
"What's he got?"
"Records. Property deeds. Lists of who pays what. Plus cash—he skims. Vincent knows, doesn't care as long as the numbers work."
Ray studies the photo. "I remember him. Piece of shit. Used to shake down shop owners in Boyle Heights. Graduated to bigger scams."
"Where's he keep it?"
"Storage unit. East LA. He's paranoid, doesn't keep anything at home." Ray looks at me. "You already knew that."
"I've been watching him for a week."
"Jesus, Cole. Do you sleep?"
"Not anymore." I tap ash into a Coke can. "Delgado makes his weekly collection run tonight. Brings everything to his unit. Stores it. Locks up. Leaves around eleven forty-five."
"So we go in at midnight."
"Thirty-minute window before he comes back for his next pickup."
Ray stands, walks to the wall, traces the connections. "Two people isn't enough."
"It's what we have."
"What if something goes wrong?"
"Then we improvise. Like old times."
He almost smiles. "Old times usually ended with someone getting shot."
"Yeah, but we're still here."
"Barely."
I pull out a duffel bag. Two suppressed pistols. A baseball bat. Gloves. Ski masks. Flashlights.
Ray picks up the bat. Tests the weight. "Subtle."
"We're not trying to be subtle. We're trying to send a message."
"What message?"
"That Vincent's people aren't untouchable."
Ray sets the bat down. Looks at me. "You know this is suicide."
"I've known that for three weeks."
"And you're doing it anyway."
"What else am I gonna do? Keep laundering blood money until Vincent gets bored and kills me? Watch my daughter grow up thinking her dad was too much of a coward to fight back?" I crush out the cigarette. "I'm already dead, Ray. I'm just deciding how I go out."
Long silence.
"Fuck it," Ray says finally. "Let's go rob a scumbag."

We spend the rest of the day on surveillance.
Delgado's routine is clockwork. He hits five buildings. Collects envelopes. Fat stacks of cash from tenants paying under the table, from businesses paying protection, from everyone Vincent's got his hooks into.
We follow him in Ray's car. Keep our distance. Professional.
At one building in South LA, we watch him intimidate an old woman. She's crying, holding out crumpled bills. Not enough. He yells. She cries harder. Eventually she goes back inside, comes back with more.
Delgado takes it. Doesn't even count it. Just stuffs it in his briefcase.
"Piece of shit," Ray mutters.
I'm looking at the building. Cross-referencing the address in my head.
"I processed that building," I say quietly. "Two years ago. Made it look like a legitimate purchase. Appraised it at eight hundred thousand. Vincent bought it for six. Made four hundred thousand in profit that was actually laundered cartel money."
Ray looks at me. "You know all of them?"
"Forty-seven buildings." I light another cigarette. "I remember every one."
"Jesus."
"The old woman? She's paying rent that I helped make 'legal.' Her money goes to Delgado, who gives it to Vincent, who uses it to buy more buildings, which I make legitimate, which bleeds more families." I exhale smoke. "It's a machine. And I'm a cog in it."
"That why we're doing this?"
"That's why I'm doing this. You're just here for the thrill."
Ray almost laughs. "Yeah. My life's real thrilling."
We watch Delgado finish his rounds. By eleven PM, he's heading to his storage facility. East LA. Commercial place. Rows of units. Minimal security. One camera at the entrance, easily avoided.
We watch him pull in. Go to unit forty-seven. Unlock it. Go inside. Come out ten minutes later with an empty briefcase.
Drives away.
We wait in the car. Parked two rows over, lights off.
"Thirty minutes," I say.
Ray's loading his old service weapon. No suppressor. Loud if he has to use it.
"You good?" I ask.
"No. But I'm here."
We pull on gloves. Ski masks in our pockets—we'll put them on before we go in. The darkness helps, but we're not taking chances. If Delgado's guys see our faces, Vincent knows. And if Vincent knows, we're dead before morning.
Eleven fifty-eight.
"Let's move."
We get out. Pull on the masks. Ray grabs the bat from the back seat. I check my suppressed pistol. Full mag.
The storage facility is quiet. Just the hum of streetlights and distant traffic.
We approach unit forty-seven. Ray pulls out his lock picks—old cop skills, never go away. Thirty seconds later, the lock clicks.
We're about to go in when—
Sound.
From inside the unit.
We both freeze.
Someone's already in there.
Ray and I exchange looks through the masks. He points: You go right, I'll go left.
I nod.
He counts down on his fingers. Three. Two. One.
We go in fast.

The unit's bigger than I expected. Rows of file cabinets. Boxes stacked high. A safe in the corner.
And crouched at that safe, working the lock with a crowbar, is a figure in all black. Hoodie up. Hasn't heard us yet.
Ray and I split. Professional. Silent. Ray moves left with the bat. I flank right with the pistol.
The figure hears something. Turns.
Flashlight beam hits their face—can't see features, just the outline of someone young, quick.
We all freeze.
Three people. Three weapons.
My suppressed pistol aimed at center mass. Ray's bat cocked back. The figure's got the crowbar raised defensively.
"Who the fuck are you?" I keep my voice low.
"Who the fuck are YOU?" Street accent. Young. Male.
"We asked first," Ray says. "Drop the crowbar."
"I drop this, you shoot me."
"I shoot you anyway if you don't answer."
The kid's smart. Doesn't move. Calculating odds.
Then—
Outside—
Car doors SLAM.
All three of us freeze.
Voices. Multiple. Getting closer.
"I'm telling you, I heard something. Check the unit."
Delgado. And he brought friends.
Footsteps. Heavy. At least four, maybe five.
Ray looks at me. I look at the kid.
"How many exits?" Ray asks him.
"One. The one they're about to come through."
"Fuck," I mutter.
"We fight our way out?" Ray's already shifting his grip on the bat.
"Three of us against how many?"
The kid, still hands up, crowbar ready: "Five. Maybe six. Delgado plus his crew."
I look at him. "How do you know?"
"Because I've been watching him all week. Same as you, apparently."
Smart kid.
The lock rattles. Someone's opening it from outside.
Ray lowers his bat slightly. "New plan. We work together. Get out alive. THEN we figure out who the fuck everyone is."
I look at the kid. "You in?"
He hesitates. Then lowers the crowbar an inch. "Do I have a choice?"
"No."
"Then I'm in."
The door swings open.
Two thugs. Guns drawn. Big guys. Delgado's muscle.
"I told you I heard—"
Ray doesn't let him finish.
Swings the bat—CRACK—right into Thug One's knee. The guy goes down screaming. Ray follows through—bat to the ribs. Brutal. Efficient.
I aim. Two quick shots—THWIP THWIP—Thug Two's shoulder and thigh. Non-lethal. He drops, clutching his leg, gun skittering across the concrete.
The kid moves—fast—rolls behind a file cabinet. Grabs the dropped gun. Aims at the door.
"More coming!"
Outside: "JESUS CHRIST THEY'RE SHOOTING—"
"GET IN THERE—"
Three more charge through.
"Ray, left!"
He's already moving. Baseball bat up. Defensive stance.
Thug Three rushes him. Ray sidesteps—bat to the back of the head. Guy drops like a sack.
I'm firing—THWIP THWIP THWIP—hitting arms, legs, keeping them down. Not trying to kill. Just incapacitate.
The kid fires twice—BANG BANG—loud, no suppressor. Forces the others back into cover.
"You're loud!" I shout at him.
"It's called suppressing fire, ese!"
Ray smashes another guy with the bat. "I like him!"
Last one through the door is BIG. Six-four, two-fifty easy. Charges like a bull.
"Ray!" I shout.
"I see him!"
Ray throws the bat—hits Big Guy in the chest, staggers him.
I rush in—pistol-whip across the face.
The kid sweeps his legs from behind with the crowbar.
Big Guy goes DOWN.
Ray finishes it—kick to the head. Lights out.
Silence.
Five bodies. Groaning. Bleeding. Alive, but out.
We're all breathing hard.
"We need to move," Ray says. "Cops are coming."
I turn to the kid. "The safe. Can you open it?"
He looks at me. Even through the ski mask, I can see him calculating.
"Give me two minutes."
"You have one."
He goes to work. Fast. Professional. Knows what he's doing.
Ray covers the door. Bat ready. I watch the kid crack the safe in forty seconds.
"Where'd you learn that?" I ask.
"YouTube."
Ray snorts. "Bullshit."
The kid pauses. "Okay, my dad taught me. Before you guys killed him."
Everything stops.
Ray goes completely still.
I stare at the kid. "What did you say?"
CLICK.
Safe opens.
"Got it." The kid starts grabbing files, stacks of cash. "We taking this or what?"
Sirens. Distant but getting closer.
"We're leaving. NOW."
We grab what we can. Files. Cash. Evidence. Stuff it into the duffel bags we brought.
Run for the exit.
Behind us, Delgado's guys are groaning, trying to get up. Won't matter. They never saw our faces. Too dark, too fast, masks on the whole time.

Parking lot.
Two cars. Ray's sedan. A beat-up Honda Civic.
We stop. Ten feet apart. Guns and weapons still half-raised.
I pull off my ski mask. Ray does the same.
The kid pulls his down.
Mid-twenties. Latino. Sharp eyes. Looking at us like he's seeing ghosts.
"Who are you?" I ask.
"Mateo Navarro." He looks right at Ray. "And you just cost me twenty grand."
Ray's face goes white. "Navarro?"
The kid's eyes narrow. "Yeah. Why? You know that name?"
Ray can't speak.
Sirens getting LOUDER.
"We don't have time for this," I say. "Meet us tomorrow. I'll text you where."
Mateo stares at me. "How the fuck do you have my number?"
"Because I'm good at what I do." I'm already getting in the car. "Ray. Move."
Ray's still frozen, staring at the kid.
"RAY."
He snaps out of it. Gets in.
We peel out. Different directions. Mateo stands there for a second, holding his duffel bag, watching us go.
Then he gets in his Honda and disappears into the night.

Ray and I don't talk until we're ten miles away.
Finally, he speaks. Voice shaking.
"Navarro."
"I heard."
"Ricardo Navarro. The traffic stop. Eight years ago."
I glance at him. "You were there."
"I was there." His hands are trembling. "I watched them kill him. And I did nothing."
"That's his son."
"Yeah." Ray's staring out the window. "That's his son."
We drive in silence.
My phone buzzes. Text from an unknown number.
Tomorrow. Noon. Griffith Park Observatory. Come alone or I disappear.
I show it to Ray.
"He's smart," Ray says quietly.
"Yeah."
"He's gonna kill me when he finds out."
"Probably."
Ray laughs. Dark. Broken. "Good. Save me the trouble of doing it myself."
I light a cigarette. Hands steady despite everything.
In the back seat: three duffel bags full of evidence. Property records. Cash. Proof of Vincent's operations.
Our first hit. Successful.
But now we've got a third player. And he's got a reason to hate at least one of us.
This is gonna get messy.
